label.value: Renal Clearance from T1 to T2 Normalized by Dose

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the dose.

label.value: Renal Clearance from T1 to T2 Normalized by Surface Area

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the surface area.

label.value: Renal Clearance from T1 to T2 Normalized by Weight

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys over the interval from T1 to T2 divided by the weight.

label.value: Renal Clearance for Dose Interval Normalized by Body Mass Index

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys, calculated using the area under the curve over the dosing interval, divided by the body mass index.

label.value: Renal Clearance for Dose Interval Normalized by Dose

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys, calculated using the area under the curve over the dosing interval, divided by the dose.

label.value: Renal Clearance for Dose Interval Normalized by Surface Area

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys, calculated using the area under the curve over the dosing interval, divided by the surface area.

label.value: Renal Clearance for Dose Interval Normalized by Weight

value.value: The clearance of a substance from the blood by the kidneys, calculated using the area under the curve over the dosing interval, divided by the weight.

label.value: Stationarity Ratio Area Under the Curve

value.value: The area under the curve (AUCTAU) at steady state divided by the area under the curve extrapolated to infinity for the initial dosing interval.

label.value: Trough Peak Ratio

value.value: The concentration at the start of a dosing interval divided by the maximum concentration during the dosing interval.

label.value: Sublingual Salivary Gland

value.value: A salivary gland located under the tongue in the floor of the oral cavity.

label.value: PROMIS Adult Social Health Domain

value.value: A Patient Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System (PROMIS) domain that assesses the status of an individual's social health.

label.value: Ability to Participate in Social Roles and Activities Subordinate Domain

value.value: The collection of PROMIS item scales that assess an individual's perceived ability to perform their usual social roles and activities.

label.value: Have Trouble Doing the Work that is Important to Me

value.value: A question about whether an individual has or had trouble doing all of the work that is really important to them.

label.value: Emotional Distress-Anxiety Subordinate Domain

value.value: The collection of PROMIS item scales that assess fear, anxious misery, hyperarousal, and somatic symptoms related to arousal.

label.value: Feel Anxious

value.value: A question about whether an individual feels or felt anxious.

label.value: Feel Worried

value.value: A question about whether an individual feels or felt worried.

label.value: PROMIS Adult Physical Health Domain

value.value: A Patient Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System (PROMIS) domain that assesses the status of an individual's physical health.

label.value: Fatigue Subordinate Domain

value.value: The collection of PROMIS item scales that assess fatigue that is likely to decrease an individual's ability to carry out daily activities, including the ability to work effectively and to function at their usual level in family or social roles.

label.value: How Often Feel Tired

value.value: A question about how often an individual feels or felt tired.

label.value: How Often Experience Extreme Exhaustion

value.value: A question about how often an individual experiences or experienced extreme exhaustion.

label.value: Tonsillar Fossa

value.value: A triangular shaped space that lies on each side of the oropharynx and houses the palatine tonsils.

label.value: How Often Run Out of Energy

value.value: A question about how often an individual ran or runs out of energy.

label.value: How Often Did Fatigue Limit Work

value.value: A question about how often fatigue limits an individual at work.

label.value: How Often Too Tired to Think Clearly

value.value: A question about how often an individual is or was too tired to think clearly.

label.value: How Often Too Tired to Bathe or Shower

value.value: A question about how often an individual is or was too tired to take a bath or shower.

label.value: How Often Have Enough Energy to Exercise Strenuously

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had enough energy to exercise strenuously.

label.value: PROMIS Adult Global Health Domain

value.value: A Patient Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System (PROMIS) domain that assesses overall health in general, including global ratings of the five primary PROMIS domains (physical function, fatigue, pain, emotional distress, social health) as well as perceptions of general health that cut across domains.

label.value: Physical Function Subordinate Domain

value.value: The collection of PROMIS item scales that assess an individual's ability to carry out activities that require physical actions including more complex activities that require a combination of skills, often within a social context.

label.value: Current Health Limits Vigorous Activities

value.value: A question about whether an individual's current health limits them in doing vigorous activities.

label.value: Current Health Limits Walking More Than a Mile

value.value: A question about whether an individual's current health limits them in walking more than a mile.

label.value: Current Health Limits Climbing One Flight of Stairs

value.value: A question about whether an individual's current health limits them in climbing one flight of stairs.

label.value: Tonsillar Pillar

value.value: The anterior and posterior borders of the tonsillar fossa.  They are composed of muscle tissue.

label.value: Current Health Limits Bending, Kneeling or Stooping

value.value: A question about whether an individual's current health limits them in bending, kneeling, or stooping.

label.value: Ability to Dress Yourself

value.value: A question about the ability of an individual to dress, including tying shoelaces and doing buttons.

label.value: Ability to Shampoo Your Hair

value.value: A question about the ability of an individual to shampoo their hair.

label.value: Ability to Wash and Dry Your Body

value.value: A question about the ability of an individual to wash and dry their body.

label.value: Ability to Get On and Off the Toilet

value.value: A question about the ability of an individual to get on and off the toilet.

label.value: PROMIS Cognitive Function Subordinate Domain

value.value: The collection of PROMIS item scales that assess perceived difficulties in intellectual processes, capabilities, and deficits.

label.value: Seems Like Brain is Not Working as Well as Usual

value.value: A question about how often it seems like an individual's brain is not working as well as usual.

label.value: Have Trouble Adding or Subtracting Numbers in My Head

value.value: A question about how often an individual has or had trouble adding or subtracting numbers in their head.

label.value: Hypomethylation Therapy

value.value: Therapies that target the activity of DNA methyltransferases. Hypomethylating agents, including azacitidine and decitabine, have been used in the therapy of myelodysplastic syndrome and secondary acute myeloid leukemia. Although it is not curative, it can induce an improvement in hematopoiesis and lead to prolonged overall survival. Use of hypomethylating agents in the treatment of sickle cell anemia and other hemoglobin disorders can trigger the expression of fetal hemoglobin, leading to significant improvements in clinical symptoms.

label.value: Vallecula

value.value: A groove between the base of the tongue and the epiglottis.

label.value: Asthma Control Questionnaire

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by Juniper et al in 1999, which is used to assess both the adequacy of and change in asthma control. This questionnaire contains 7 items using a 7-point scale.

label.value: ADHD Rating Scale-IV Home Version Questionnaire

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by DuPaul et al in 1998 based on the DSM-IV criteria, which is used for the diagnosis of ADHD in children and adolescents, and for the assessment of treatment response. This questionnaire requires a subject to rate the frequency and severity of inattentive and hyperactive-impulsive symptoms on a scale of 0 to 3: never or rarely (0), sometimes (1), often (2), or very often (3).

label.value: Asthma Quality of Life Questionnaire

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by Juniper et al in 1992, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in patients with asthma. This questionnaire contains 32 items using a 7-point scale, and the items are grouped into four domains: activity limitations, symptoms, emotional function, and exposure to environmental stimuli.

label.value: Hemophilia Quality of Life Questionnaire Children's Long Version Age Group I

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by the Haemo-QoL Study Group in 2002, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in children and adolescents with hemophilia. The children's long version age group I questionnaire contains 21 items for children 4 to 7 years of age.

label.value: Hemophilia Quality of Life Questionnaire Children's Long Version Age Group II

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by the Haemo-QoL Study Group in 2002, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in children and adolescents with hemophilia. The children's long version age group II questionnaire contains 64 items for children 8 to 12 years of age.

label.value: Hemophilia Quality of Life Questionnaire Children's Long Version Age Group III

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by the Haemo-QoL Study Group in 2002, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in children and adolescents with hemophilia. The children's long version age group III questionnaire contains 77 items for adolescents 13 to 16 years of age.

label.value: Hemophilia Quality of Life Questionnaire Children's Short Version Age Group I

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by the Haemo-QoL Study Group in 2002, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in children and adolescents with hemophilia. The children's short version age group I questionnaire contains 16 items for children 4 to 7 years of age.

label.value: Hemophilia Quality of Life Questionnaire Children's Short Version Age Group II/III

value.value: A standardized rating scale developed by the Haemo-QoL Study Group in 2002, which is used to measure the physical and emotional impacts on quality of life in children and adolescents with hemophilia. The children's short version age group II/III questionnaire contains 35 items, which can be used for both children 8 to 12 years of age and adolescents 13 to 16 years of age.
